[normal]About Rabbis for Human Rights [bold]Founded in 1988, Rabbis for Human Rights is the only rabbinic voice in Israel that is explicitly dedicated to human rights.  Representing 100 Israeli rabbis and rabbinical students from different streams of Judaism, we 
[normal]derive our authority from our Jewish 
[normal]tradition and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.   Our mission is to inform the Israeli public about human rights violations, and to pressure the State institutions to redress these injustices.  In a time in which a nationalist and isolationist und
[normal]erstanding of Jewish tradition is heard frequently and loudly, Rabbis for Human Rights give expression to the traditional Jewish responsibility for the safety and welfare of the stranger, the different and the weak, the convert, the widow and the orphan.
[normal] [bold]RHR works primarily in fields where we think our rabbinic voice will be most effective: 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Human Rights Work in the Occupied Territories[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Olive Tree Campaign[bold]:[bold] RHR 
[normal]works year round with Palestinian farmers from several dozen villages in the Occupied Territor
[normal]ies, to ensure that they can regularly access their agricultural lands, often denied to them because of their proximity to Israeli settlements.  We negotiate and coordinate with the army to ensure the High Court mandate military protection during the olive
[normal] harvest, and to ensure access to lands when denied.  We also bring hundreds of Israeli and international volunteers to work side by side and in solidarity with Palestinians during the olive harvest, who help provide protection against possible settler int
[normal]imidation.  We also track Israeli settler acts of damage of Palestinian trees and property, and monitor the state response.  During Tu B’shvat
[normal] (the Israeli New Year for trees)
[normal], we purchase and bring hundreds of Israeli and international volunteers together
[normal] with Palestinians to plant some 
[normal]3,000
[normal] olive trees in areas where settlers have cut, uprooted and/or burned trees in acts of vandalism and arson.  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Challenging Land Confiscation in the Occupied Territories: [bold]RHR works to legally prevent or reverse the take
[normal]over of Palestinian lands in Area C, and ensure that Palestinian farmers can safely access those lands.  We started working in villages in the South Hebron Hills
[normal] in 2005
[normal], and in the past year, we have expanded to the villages around Bethlehem as well as to
[normal] a few villages in the Northern West Bank. In the coming year, we will continue to monitor the implementation of previous rulings on land access issues, and currently are working on 20
[normal]3
[normal] open cases relating to land confiscation and criminal charges and comp
[normal]laints lodged by Palestinian farmers against settlement security personnel.  
[normal]&#xa0;
